# DPI Engine 🔍

![C++](https://img.shields.io/badge/Language-C++17-blue)
![Networking](https://img.shields.io/badge/Domain-Networking-orange)
![Status](https://img.shields.io/badge/Status-Complete-success)

**DPI Engine** is a **Deep Packet Inspection system** written in C++. It reads network traffic from a file, looks inside each packet to identify which app it belongs to (YouTube, Facebook, etc.), and blocks or forwards traffic based on rules you define.

---

## 🤔 What is Deep Packet Inspection?

When you visit a website, your data travels as small chunks called **packets**. A normal firewall only checks *where* a packet is going. DPI goes deeper — it looks *inside* the packet to see *what app* is sending it.

Think of it like this:
- Normal firewall = checking the address on an envelope
- DPI = opening the envelope and reading what's inside

---

## 💡 The Core Idea — How We Identify Apps

Even though HTTPS traffic is encrypted, there is **one thing that is always visible** — the domain name.

When your browser connects to `https://www.youtube.com`, it sends a message called a **TLS Client Hello**. This message contains the domain name in plain text — this is called the **SNI (Server Name Indication)**.

```
Your Browser → sends TLS Client Hello → contains "www.youtube.com" ← we read THIS
               (everything after this is encrypted)
```

So even though we cannot read what you are watching on YouTube, we can see that you are connecting to YouTube. That is enough to block it.

---

## 🔄 How a Packet Flows Through the System

Every packet goes through these steps:

**1. Read** — Load the packet from a `.pcap` file (network capture file saved by tools like Wireshark)

**2. Parse** — Unpack the packet layer by layer:
- Ethernet layer → gives us MAC addresses
- IP layer → gives us source and destination IP addresses
- TCP/UDP layer → gives us port numbers

**3. Identify the connection** — Every connection is identified by 5 values called a **Five-Tuple**:
```
Source IP + Destination IP + Source Port + Destination Port + Protocol
```
All packets with the same five values belong to the same connection.

**4. Inspect** — Look inside the packet payload:
- If port is 443 (HTTPS) → extract the SNI to get the domain name
- If port is 80 (HTTP) → extract the Host header to get the domain name
- Map the domain to an app: `youtube.com` → YouTube, `facebook.com` → Facebook

**5. Check rules** — Should this packet be blocked?
- Is the source IP in the blocked list?
- Is the app (YouTube, TikTok) in the blocked list?
- Does the domain name match a blocked keyword?

**6. Forward or Drop** — If blocked, the packet is thrown away. If not, it is written to the output file.

---

## 🏗 Two Versions

### Simple Version (`main_working.cpp`)
- Processes one packet at a time
- Easy to understand
- Good for small captures

### Multi-threaded Version (`dpi_mt.cpp`)
- Processes many packets at the same time using multiple threads
- Much faster for large captures
- Uses this pipeline:

```
Reader → Load Balancers → Fast Path Workers → Output Writer
```

The key rule in multi-threading: **all packets from the same connection always go to the same worker thread**. This is done using consistent hashing on the five-tuple. This means one thread always has the full picture of a connection and never misses the SNI.

---

## 📁 Project Structure

```
packet_analyzer/
├── include/               ← Header files (what each component does)
│   ├── pcap_reader.h      ← Reads .pcap files
│   ├── packet_parser.h    ← Parses Ethernet, IP, TCP headers
│   ├── sni_extractor.h    ← Extracts domain name from TLS/HTTP
│   ├── types.h            ← Data structures (FiveTuple, AppType)
│   └── ...
│
├── src/                   ← Implementation files (how it's done)
│   ├── main_working.cpp   ← Simple single-threaded version
│   ├── dpi_mt.cpp         ← Multi-threaded version
│   └── ...
│
└── generate_test_pcap.py  ← Creates sample traffic for testing
```

---

## ⚙️ Installation

**Requirements:** macOS or Linux, C++17 compiler (g++ or clang++)

### Build Simple Version
```bash
g++ -std=c++17 -O2 -I include -o dpi_simple \
    src/main_working.cpp \
    src/pcap_reader.cpp \
    src/packet_parser.cpp \
    src/sni_extractor.cpp \
    src/types.cpp
```

### Build Multi-threaded Version
```bash
g++ -std=c++17 -pthread -O2 -I include -o dpi_engine \
    src/dpi_mt.cpp \
    src/pcap_reader.cpp \
    src/packet_parser.cpp \
    src/sni_extractor.cpp \
    src/types.cpp
```

---

## 🚀 Running

### Basic — just analyze traffic
```bash
./dpi_engine input.pcap output.pcap
```

### With blocking rules
```bash
./dpi_engine input.pcap output.pcap \
    --block-app YouTube \
    --block-app TikTok \
    --block-ip 192.168.1.50 \
    --block-domain facebook
```

### Control number of threads
```bash
./dpi_engine input.pcap output.pcap --lbs 4 --fps 4
```

### Generate test traffic
```bash
python3 generate_test_pcap.py
```

