---

## 🔒 Blocking Rules Explained

There are 3 ways to block traffic:

| Rule | Example | What gets blocked |
|------|---------|-------------------|
| Block by IP | `192.168.1.50` | All traffic from that device |
| Block by App | `YouTube` | All YouTube connections |
| Block by Domain | `tiktok` | Any domain containing "tiktok" |

**Important:** Blocking works at the connection level. The first few packets of a connection are always forwarded because we haven't seen the domain name yet. Once we see the SNI in the Client Hello packet, we mark the entire connection as blocked and drop all packets from that connection from that point on.

---

## ❓ Common Questions

**Q: Why can we see the domain name even in HTTPS?**
The domain name is sent before encryption starts. It is in the TLS Client Hello message in plain text. After that first message, everything is encrypted and we cannot read it.

**Q: Why does the same connection always go to the same thread?**
Because we need to track the state of a connection. If packets went to different threads, one thread might see the SNI and another might not, and blocking would break. Consistent hashing on the five-tuple solves this.

**Q: What is a .pcap file?**
It is a file that stores recorded network traffic. Tools like Wireshark can create them. Our engine reads these files instead of live network traffic.

**Q: What if a packet has no SNI?**
It gets classified as UNKNOWN or HTTPS (if on port 443) and is forwarded unless the IP itself is blocked.

